}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name        = Friends & Enemies \n| type        = compilation\n| artist      = [[Fred Frith]] and [[Henry Kaiser (musician)|Henry Kaiser]]\n| cover       = Frith&Kaiser AlbumCover Friends&Enemies.jpg\n| released    = {{Start date|1999|06}}\n| recorded    = July 1979, October 1983, October 1984 (live sets), January 1999\n| studio      = Mobius Music, San Francisco\n| venue       = Wolfgangs, [[San Francisco]]; McCabe's, [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]]; Kuuwumba Jazz Society, [[Santa Cruz, California|Santa Cruz]]\n| genre       = [[Experimental music]], [[free improvisation]], [[noise music|noise]]\n| length      = {{Duration|m=158|s=50}}\n| label       = [[Cuneiform Records|Cuneiform]] (US)\n| producer    = [[Henry Kaiser (musician)|Henry Kaiser]], [[Fred Frith]]\n| prev_title  = With Enemies Like These, Who Needs Friends?\n| prev_year   = 1987\n}}\n\n'''''Friends & Enemies''''' is a 1999 double-CD [[compilation album]] of studio and live material by [[Fred Frith]] and [[Henry Kaiser (musician)|Henry Kaiser]]. It contains the complete collaborative recordings of Frith and Kaiser from 1979 to 1999, namely their two studio albums ''[[With Friends Like These (album)|With Friends Like These]]'' (1979) and ''[[Who Needs Enemies? (album)|Who Needs Enemies?]]'' (1983), an unreleased live album recorded in 1984, and new studio tracks recorded in 1999. The album was released by [[Cuneiform Records]] in June 1999.\n\n==Background==\nOliver DiCicco was the engineer for Frith and Kaiser's two collaborative albums, ''[[With Friends Like These (album)|With Friends Like These]]'' and ''[[Who Needs Enemies? (album)|Who Needs Enemies?]]'' at Mobius Music in [[San Francisco]], and for the 1999 studio sessions, also at Mobius Music. DiCicco wrote in the ''Friends & Enemies'' liner notes that during these recording sessions he \"was free to become part of the creative team in a way that transcended mere audio engineering\".<ref name=LinerNotes/> He said that this creativity \"enriched my life and inspired my own artistry\".<ref name=LinerNotes/>\n\nDiCicco noted that the duo \"possess a very special chemistry\", with Frith contributing \"compositional and melodic aesthetic\", and Kaiser adding \"an unfettered approach to sound and guitar technique\".<ref name=LinerNotes/> While making ''With Friends Like These'' in 1979, and ''Who Needs Enemies?'' in 1983, DiCicco recognized the significance of what they were doing. But it was only during the 1999 studio sessions that he realised how \"far ahead of their time\" those recording were.<ref name=LinerNotes/> DiCicco said their utilization of noise \"predates most of the 'out' genre that followed\", and the [[LinnDrum]] programming on ''Who Needs Enemies?'' and the unreleased live album \"predated the '90s [[drum and bass|drum 'n' bass]] music by more than a decade\".<ref name=LinerNotes/>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=Anderson/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev2Score = Favorable<ref name=Lewis/>\n}}\nIn a review of ''Friends & Enemies'' in [[AllMusic]], Rick Anderson described Frith and Kaiser's first collaboration, ''With Friends Like These'' as \"one of the defining documents of the downtown avant-garde scene\", and said their improvised duets \"essentially redefined the sound of the guitar\".<ref name=Anderson/> He complimented [[Cuneiform Records]] on including all of the duo's recorded work in this compilation, and called it \"a must for noise fans, skronk hounds, and adventurous guitarheads\".<ref name=Anderson/>\n\nWriting in ''[[Exclaim!]]'', David Lewis described the evolution of Frith and Kaiser's collaborations, from the [[Derek Bailey (guitarist)|Derek Bailey]]-inspired improvisations with \"skewed riff and oddball time signatures\" in ''With Friends Like These'', to their inclusion of drum machines and other technologies in ''Who Needs Enemies?'' and their unreleased live album\u2014which Lewis said gave their music \"a dated and cheesy appeal\", to their latest collaborations in 1999 where they blend new technologies with the \"purity and beauty\" of their first album.<ref name=Lewis/> Lewis called ''Friends & Enemies'' \"essential guitar music\", and \"[a] gem\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll music by [[Fred Frith]] and [[Henry Kaiser (musician)|Henry Kaiser]], except where noted.\n{{track listing\n| headline = CD 1\n| extra_column = Original album\n| title_width = 26em\n| extra_width = 20em\n| title1 = It Moves ...\n| extra1 = ''[[With Friends Like These (album)|With Friends Like These]]'' <small>(1979)</small>\n| length1 = 2:07\n| title2 = The Changing of Names\n| extra2 = ''With Friends Like These''\n| length2 = 5:47\n| title3 = It Sings\n| extra3 = ''With Friends Like These''\n| length3 = 5:40\n| title4 = Believing What We Read\n| extra4 = ''With Friends Like These''\n| length4 = 3:02\n| title5 = ...But Does It Swing?\n| extra5 = ''With Friends Like These''\n| length5 = 3:31\n| title6 = Hard Time Killin' Floor Blues\n| note6 = [[Skip James|Nehemiah \"Skip\" James]]\n| extra6 = ''[[Who Needs Enemies? (album)|Who Needs Enemies?]]'' <small>(1983)</small>\n| length6 = 3:31\n| title7 = The Golden Eighties\n| extra7 = ''Who Needs Enemies?''\n| length7 = 5:46\n| title8 = Everyday Objects\n| extra8 = ''Who Needs Enemies?''\n| length8 = 2:49\n| title9 = The Kirghiz Light\n| extra9 = ''Who Needs Enemies?''\n| length9 = 4:55\n| title10 = Special Rider Blues\n| note10 = James\n| extra10 = ''Who Needs Enemies?''\n| length10 = 4:31\n| title11 = Drowsy Maggie\n| extra11 = Unreleased live album <small>(recorded 1984)</small>\n| length11 = 4:06\n| title12 = An HK Guitar Solo\n| note12 = Kaiser\n| extra12 = Unreleased live album\n| length12 = 3:32\n| title13 = Strandloper\n| extra13 = Unreleased live album\n| length13 = 1:17\n| title14 = Major Nichols\n| extra14 = Unreleased live album\n| length14 = 3:53\n| title15 = The Live Trace\n| extra15 = Unrel